fields.name: Pull-Ups
fields.description: Pull-ups are a strength-building exercise that primarily targets the muscles of the upper body, including the latissimus dorsi (lats), biceps brachii, and rear deltoids. This exercise is an effective way to test and enhance upper body strength and muscular endurance. By suspending from a horizontal bar and lifting your bodyweight, it challenges your ability to pull yourself up, making it an excellent exercise for developing a strong back and arm muscles.

fields.name: Push-Ups
fields.description: Push-ups are a versatile bodyweight exercise that primarily targets the muscles of the chest, shoulders, and triceps. They are an effective way to test and improve upper body strength and muscular endurance. In a push-up, you start in a plank position with your hands shoulder-width apart, lower your body by bending your arms, and then push back up to the starting position. This exercise helps build a strong chest and upper body while also engaging the core for stability. Push-ups can be adapted for different fitness levels, making them a valuable conditioning exercise.

fields.name: Lateral Jump Right
fields.description: Lateral jumps are a plyometric exercise that focuses on testing and enhancing lower body strength, agility, and explosiveness. In a lateral jump, you begin by standing with your feet together, then jump horizontally to the side, landing on one foot and immediately jumping back to the other side. This exercise primarily targets the muscles in the legs, including the quadriceps, hamstrings, and calves, while also engaging the hip abductors and adductors for lateral stability. Lateral jumps are an excellent way to improve athletic performance and coordination.

fields.name: Lateral Jump Left
fields.description: Lateral jumps are a plyometric exercise that focuses on testing and enhancing lower body strength, agility, and explosiveness. In a lateral jump, you begin by standing with your feet together, then jump horizontally to the side, landing on one foot and immediately jumping back to the other side. This exercise primarily targets the muscles in the legs, including the quadriceps, hamstrings, and calves, while also engaging the hip abductors and adductors for lateral stability. Lateral jumps are an excellent way to improve athletic performance and coordination.

fields.name: Broad Jump
fields.description: The broad jump, also known as the long jump, is an explosive exercise that tests and develops lower body power, particularly in the muscles of the legs and hips. In a broad jump, you start from a standing position and explosively push off with your legs to jump as far forward as possible. This exercise primarily targets the quadriceps, hamstrings, glutes, and calves. It challenges your ability to generate maximum force and control your body during a dynamic leap, making it an effective exercise for improving athletic performance, leg strength, and overall lower body conditioning.

fields.name: Vertical Jump
fields.description: The vertical jump is a measure of lower body explosiveness and power. It assesses an individual's ability to jump vertically as high as possible from a stationary position. This exercise primarily targets the muscles of the legs, including the quadriceps, hamstrings, glutes, and calf muscles. It also engages the core muscles for stability during takeoff and landing. Vertical jumps are commonly used in sports and fitness assessments to evaluate an individual's athleticism and leg strength. Training to improve your vertical jump can enhance your ability to perform various athletic activities, including basketball, volleyball, and track and field events.

fields.name: Medball Toss
fields.description: The medball toss is a dynamic exercise that involves throwing a medicine ball explosively. It is designed to test and develop upper body power, strength, and coordination. In a medball toss, you typically stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, hold a medicine ball, and forcefully throw it either vertically or horizontally, depending on the specific variation. This exercise primarily targets the muscles of the chest, shoulders, triceps, and core as you generate power to propel the ball. Medball tosses are commonly used in sports training and fitness programs to improve athletic performance and overall upper body conditioning.

fields.name: Pro Agility
fields.description:
The Pro-Agility Test, also known as the 5-10-5 Shuttle or the 20-Yard Shuttle, is a common agility test used in sports and fitness assessments. It evaluates an individual's ability to quickly change direction, accelerate, and decelerate.

In this test, the participant starts in a three-point stance at the center of a 10-yard (or 9.14 meters) distance. Upon a signal or command, they sprint 5 yards (4.57 meters) to one side, touch the ground with their hand, change direction, and sprint 10 yards (9.14 meters) to the opposite side, touching the ground again. Finally, they sprint back to the center 5-yard point. The test measures the time it takes to complete this back-and-forth shuttle run.

The Pro-Agility Test assesses agility, lateral quickness, and acceleration, making it valuable for sports such as football, soccer, basketball, and any other activities that require rapid changes in direction. It is often used to gauge an athlete's agility and speed in short bursts.

fields.name: 10 Yard Acceleration
fields.description:
The 10-yard acceleration test is a sprinting assessment designed to evaluate an individual's ability to rapidly accelerate from a stationary position over a short distance of 10 yards (approximately 9.14 meters).

Participants start from a stationary position, often in a three-point stance or a standing start. Upon a signal or command, they explosively sprint for the designated 10-yard distance as quickly as possible. This test measures the time it takes to cover the 10-yard distance from a dead stop.

The 10-yard acceleration test is commonly used in sports like football, track and field, and other activities that require quick bursts of speed from a static position. It helps assess an athlete's initial acceleration and explosiveness, which can be critical in various sports and competitions.

fields.name: Plate Pinch Hold Right
fields.description:
The plate pinch hold is a grip strength exercise that involves holding weight plates (typically of varying thicknesses) using only the fingertips and thumb, pinching them together without any support from the palm or fingers' wrapping motion.

To perform a plate pinch hold, you take two weight plates of your choice, grip them between your fingers and thumb, and lift them off the ground. You then attempt to maintain this pinch grip for as long as possible.

This exercise primarily targets the muscles of the fingers, thumb, and forearm. It is an effective way to test and improve grip strength, which is essential in activities such as weightlifting, rock climbing, and various sports where maintaining a firm grip is crucial. The plate pinch hold can be adapted by using plates of different weights and thicknesses to progressively challenge grip strength.

fields.name: W Hold
fields.description:
The W hold for scapulas is a corrective exercise aimed at strengthening and stabilizing the muscles around the shoulder blades, particularly the rhomboids and lower trapezius muscles.

The W hold for scapulas is an excellent exercise for correcting poor posture, improving scapular stability, and countering the effects of prolonged sitting and slouching. It can help alleviate shoulder and neck discomfort while promoting better shoulder blade positioning.

fields.name: Shoulder Horizontal Adduction Right
fields.description: Shoulder horizontal adduction is a movement that involves bringing your arm or shoulder closer to the centerline of your body horizontally. This action primarily engages the pectoral (chest) muscles and the anterior deltoid (front shoulder) muscles.

fields.name: Overhead Squat
fields.description: The overhead squat is a compound exercise that combines a full squat with an overhead press. It is used to assess and improve lower body strength, core stability, and shoulder mobility.

fields.name: Hurdle Right
fields.description: The hurdle mobility test is a physical assessment used to evaluate an individual's flexibility, mobility, and range of motion, particularly in the hip and lower back areas. It helps identify any restrictions or limitations in these areas that could impact an individual's performance or predispose them to injury, especially in activities requiring hip mobility.
